# JavaScript Style Guide

*This rule automatically attaches when working with JavaScript files.*

## File Organization

- **Avoid inline JavaScript** in HTML/Jinja templates
- Place JavaScript in external `.js` files
- Organize by functionality (not all code in one file)
- Use ES6+ modules when possible
- Keep files focused and single-purpose

## Script Loading

- Load scripts at the bottom of `<body>` or use `defer`/`async`
- Use `defer` for scripts that need DOM to be ready
- Use `async` for independent scripts that don't need DOM
- Document script dependencies clearly

## Code Style

- Use modern ES6+ syntax (const/let, arrow functions, template literals)
- Use consistent indentation (2 spaces recommended)
- Use semicolons consistently (or not, but be consistent)
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Comment complex logic

## Library Management

- Document all JavaScript libraries and their purposes
- Use a package manager (npm, yarn) when possible
- Keep library versions consistent
- Minimize the number of external libraries
- Load libraries from CDN or bundle them, but be consistent

## DOM Manipulation

- Wait for DOM to be ready before manipulating
- Use modern methods (`querySelector`, `addEventListener`)
- Avoid inline event handlers in HTML
- Use event delegation when appropriate

## Example Structure

```javascript
// Wait for DOM
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
  // Initialize app
  initApp();
});

// Use modules when possible
import { utilityFunction } from './utils.js';

// Organize by functionality
function initApp() {
  setupEventListeners();
  loadData();
}

function setupEventListeners() {
  // Event handling
}
```

## Anti-Patterns

- ❌ Inline JavaScript in HTML
- ❌ Scripts in `<head>` without defer/async
- ❌ Mixing old and new JavaScript syntax
- ❌ Global variables polluting namespace
- ❌ Unorganized, monolithic JavaScript files

---

*Customize this rule with your specific JavaScript preferences and framework choices.*
